<h4 style="margin:0 0 0.75em;line-height:1.2;font-size:1.2em">
  “Why do I need to set a new password now?”
</h4>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
Because we discovered that one of your logins (your email and password) from another web site is currently listed in an online data breach, and it turns out you use that same password on your Highrise account.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
We have not detected anyone using the breached password to log in to your account.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
We removed the unsafe password from your account and disabled login until you can set up a new password.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
  ↪ <a href="https://launchpad.37signals.com/highrise/forgot_password?email_address=leanne%40epilogue.com.au" style="color:#1b6ac9">Set a new password now by clicking this link</a>
</p>


<h4 style="margin:0 0 0.75em;line-height:1.2;font-size:1.2em">
  “What exactly happened here? Was my Highrise account hacked?”
</h4>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
We found your password listed online from another web site that was hacked. This is not an alert that your Highrise account was involved in a hack.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
During a routine security scan of online data breaches, we found your email address listed along with passwords you’ve used on other web sites. That means some of your passwords are out on the internet for anyone to use. One of these breached passwords turns out to be the same one you use to log in to your Highrise account.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
To prevent anyone else from logging in to your account, we’ve disabled login until you set up a new password. You won’t be able to log in with that password anymore—but neither will anyone else who gets ahold of your password online. You’ll need to set up a brand new password so you and only you can log in to your account.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
  ↪ <a href="https://launchpad.37signals.com/highrise/forgot_password?email_address=leanne%40epilogue.com.au" style="color:#1b6ac9">Set a new password now by clicking this link</a>
</p>


<h4 style="margin:0 0 0.75em;line-height:1.2;font-size:1.2em">
  “So how did my email and passwords end up in an online data breach?”
</h4>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
Another web site you use suffered a data breach, which means a hacker got in and stole all the emails and passwords they had on file. The hacker then leaked all the emails and passwords onto the internet.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
You may have heard about these data breaches in the news in recent years. When a web site is hacked, the hackers compile and resell valuable personal data like emails, passwords, and credit cards. They use this info to log in as you to other web sites, as well as for identity theft and credit card fraud.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
As part of our ongoing work to keep your Highrise account safe, we scan these compilations of breached data to check whether your email and password are listed. In detail: we scan the data breach to look for your email. If we find it, we check for a password in the breach. We securely hash the breached password and compare it to the securely hashed password we have on file for you. If that matches, we know that the email and password in the data breach can be used to log in to your Highrise account, so we remove the unsafe password, disable login, and send you this email.
</p>


<h4 style="margin:0 0 0.75em;line-height:1.2;font-size:1.2em">
  “What can I do about this now?”
</h4>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
First, you’ve done nothing wrong. It’s very common for our personal info to appear in a data breach, including emails and passwords. Sad to say, it’s now a fact of online life. Thankfully, knowing is half the battle. There’s much we can do to protect ourselves.
</p>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
  <strong>Here’s what you can do right away:</strong>
</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <a href="https://launchpad.37signals.com/highrise/forgot_password?email_address=leanne%40epilogue.com.au" style="color:#1b6ac9">Set a new Highrise password now by clicking this link</a>.
  </li>
  <li>
    Reset your password on your email account. This is your most sensitive, important online account, so it deserves a strong password that you don’t use on any other web sites.
  </li>
  <li>
    Subscribe to a free breach notification service. If a web site you use suffers a breach, you’ll receive an alert letting you know. You can then change those passwords. We recommend <a href="https://haveibeenpwned.com" style="color:#1b6ac9">Have I Been Pwned</a>. This is a free service; there’s no catch or upsell. It’s run by a <a href="https://haveibeenpwned.com/About" style="color:#1b6ac9">concerned citizen</a> looking out for other people online.
  </li>
</ol>

<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
  <strong>Here’s what you can do in the coming weeks:</strong>
</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    Use a password manager app! They make it much easier to create and use long, complex passwords that are unique for each web site you use. Password reuse is a major risk, allowing a breach on one web site to spread to others. We use <a href="https://1password.com" style="color:#1b6ac9">1Password</a> at Basecamp and recommend it. Any reputable password manager will do a good job, including <a href="https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT204085" style="color:#1b6ac9">iCloud Keychain</a> (iOS, Mac) and <a href="https://support.google.com/chrome/answer/95606?hl=en" style="color:#1b6ac9">Google Saved Passwords</a> (Android, Chrome browser).
  </li>
  <li>
    Reset your password on web sites where you’ve used the same password as other sites. Use your password manager to generate new passwords.
  </li>
  <li>
    Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) on <a href="https://twofactorauth.org" style="color:#1b6ac9">web sites that support it</a>. Especially your email account!
  </li>
</ol>


<p style="color:#000;margin:0 0 1em">
This is a lot to tackle all at once. Take it step by step. Please feel free to reply to this email with any questions. You’ve got this, and we’re here to help.
</p>

